common: fallback to C GNU regex for compilers with limited std::regex support

This change replaces fallback to boost::regex with fallback to GNU C
regex if the compiler lacks complete support for std::regex.
See recent commit for the same.
common: Level out copyright headers

autotools: fallback to boost_regex for compilers with limited std::regex support

It has come to our attention that some compilers exhibit incomplete support
for std::regex (https://gcc.gnu.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=53631).
Although the code may compile without errors, at runtime it crashes with an
exception similar to:

  terminate called after throwing an instance of 'std::regex_error'
    what(): regex_error

This issue has been observed notably with GCC 4.8.5, which, while relatively old,
is still included in RHEL 7.x by default. As long as it remains a supported platform,
we've introduced a workaround that enables a fallback to boost::regex to address this
compatibility concern.

kernel module: fix wrong comparison order
